The start symbol S has only two productions:

1. S → NT73 NT20  
2. S → NT95 NT83  

– NT20 can generate only one terminal ('t17' or 't1') or the two-terminal sequence t33 t14.  
– NT95 is restricted to a single terminal ('t18' or 't35').  

Therefore, in any derivation from S the string must be split into two contiguous parts as follows:

• If S → NT73 NT20, the second part must be either one terminal (t17 or t1) or the two-terminal sequence t33 t14.  
• If S → NT95 NT83, the very first symbol of the string must be t18 or t35, because NT95 occupies exactly one position at the beginning.

The given 43-token string starts with t4, not t18 or t35, so the second production is impossible.

Looking at the whole string, the only occurrence of the terminal t17 is at position 12, and the pair t33 t14 never occurs (t14 is not in the string at all).  
Hence it is impossible to place NT20 as a contiguous suffix of length 1 or 2 that covers the entire remainder of the string, and so the first production is also impossible.

Since neither of the only two possible derivations from the start symbol can match the structure of the provided string, the grammar cannot generate the string.

No

The start symbol S can only expand in one of two ways:

1. S → NT73 NT20  
   The first token produced by NT73 can be  
   • t36  (from NT73 → 't36')  
   • t24 or t36 (via NT73 → NT62 NT27, NT62 → 't24' | 't36')  
   • t11 or t31 (via NT73 → NT12 NT47, NT12 → 't11' | 't31')  
   None of these possibilities start with t0.

2. S → NT95 NT83  
   NT95 is immediately a terminal: NT95 → 't18' | 't35'.  
   So the first token here must be t18 or t35, never t0.

Because the given string begins with t0, and neither of the only two possible first tokens from S can be t0, the string cannot be generated by the grammar.

Therefore the answer is:

No

The only start productions are  

S → NT73 NT20 (length ≤ 5) and  
S → NT95 NT83.

Because the given string has 40 terminals, the first alternative is impossible, so the derivation must begin with  

S → NT95 NT83.  

NT95 is a single terminal (‘t18’ or ‘t35’).  
Since the first word of the string is t18, we must take NT95 → ‘t18’.

Hence the remaining 39 words must be generated by NT83.

NT83 has the productions  

NT83 → ‘t28’ (length 1)  
NT83 → NT22 NT45.

Length 1 is impossible (39 words left), so we need NT83 → NT22 NT45.
NT22 → NT44 NT63, giving exactly two terminals.  
The second and third words of the string are t4 t29, and indeed NT44 → ‘t4’, NT63 → ‘t29’.  
So far everything matches, and 37 words remain to be produced by NT45.

NT45 has only two possibilities:

NT45 → NT2 NT95  (length 2)  
NT45 → NT44 NT52.

The first one is far too short, so NT45 must be NT44 NT52.
The next word in the string is t31, and NT44 → ‘t31’, which fits.
Therefore NT52 must generate the final 36 words of the string.

NT52 can be

NT52 → NT35 NT96 (first word would be t3/t5/t13)  
NT52 → NT80 NT47 (first word would be t7)  
NT52 → NT12 NT85 (first word would be t11 or t31).

Because the next word in the string is t11, the only viable choice is NT52 → NT12 NT85 with NT12 → ‘t11’, leaving 35 words to be generated by NT85.

NT85 has the single production NT85 → NT74 NT73, so we must split the remaining 35 words into a prefix produced by NT74 and a suffix produced by NT73.

Possible lengths generated by NT73 (listing all of its rules) are

1 :  t36  
2 :  t24 t33, t24 t27, t36 t33, t36 t27, t11 t27, t31 t27  
3 :  t11 t30 t31, t11 t30 t4, t31 t30 t31, t31 t30 t4,  
  t11 tX tY or t31 tX tY with tX ∈ {t3,t23,t9,t0,t2} and tY ∈ {t20,t2}

Looking at the last 3, 2 and 1 words of the string

… 38:t23 39:t36 40:t2  
…      39:t36 40:t2  
…        40:t2

none of the sequences (t23 t36 t2, t36 t2, t2) appears in the list above, so NT73 cannot generate the tail of the string no matter where we try to split it. Consequently NT85 cannot generate the required 35-word segment, NT52 cannot generate its 36-word segment, NT45 cannot generate 37 words, and NT83 cannot generate the remaining 39 words.

Hence the grammar cannot derive the given 40-word string.

No
